## React Patterns
- Prefer controlled components over uncontrolled ones
- Implement proper error boundaries
- Extract reusable hooks for shared logic
- Prefer abortController.signal over removeEventListener
- Must not use forwardRef from react 19 up. ref is now automatically injected into the props


## React Components
- Extract `.map()` rendering into a dedicated Item component **when the map closure exceeds 15 lines**. Simpler inline maps (e.g., basic list items, dropdown options) are acceptable.
  ```tsx
  // Acceptable: Simple inline map (under 15 lines)
  {items.map(item => (
    <SelectItem key={item.id} value={item.id}>
      {item.label}
    </SelectItem>
  ))}
  
  // Refactor: Map closure exceeds 15 lines → extract to Item component
  {records.map(record => (
    <AttendanceRecord
      key={record._id}
      record={record}
      onApprove={handleApprove}
      onReject={handleReject}
    />
  ))}
  ```
- Move constant objects/maps/sets (values that never change) outside the
  component to avoid recreating them on every render. However, if the
  module is eagerly imported (e.g., barrel export) and the component is
  rarely used, keeping them inside the component scope wrapped in
  `React.useMemo` is acceptable to avoid allocating memory for unused
  constants at module load time. Ignore this rule if react-compiler is
  enabled in the project.
  ```tsx
  // ✅ Good when component renders frequently or module is code-split
  const STATUS_COLORS = {
    open: "text-foreground",
    approved: "text-green-500",
    completed: "text-violet-500",
    rejected: "text-red-500",
  } as const;

  function StatusBadge({ status }: { status: keyof typeof STATUS_COLORS }) {
    return <span className={STATUS_COLORS[status]}>{status}</span>;
  }

  // ✅ Good when component is rarely used but module is eagerly imported
  function RarelyUsedStatusBadge({ status }: { status: string }) {
    const statusColorMap = React.useMemo(() => ({
      open: "text-foreground",
      approved: "text-green-500",
      completed: "text-violet-500",
      rejected: "text-red-500",
    } as const), []);
    return <span className={statusColorMap[status] ?? ""}>{status}</span>;
  }
  ```
